{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537201"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15913"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15913"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.07,0.11,0.55,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8604"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"4674"},{"type":"tags","id":"4699"},{"type":"tags","id":"4702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4724"},{"type":"tags","id":"4731"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8140"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44431"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following waking up disorientated at a party. She believes she was sexually assaulted as she found herself undressed and with fluid around her genitals. She has no significant medical history but did not receive her childhood immunisations. She has a copper intrauterine device and her last period was two weeks ago. She does not take any regular medications. She has already spoken with police and had forensic examination and samples collected for forensic testing. She is unsure of the assailant\u0027s medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious. Her vital signs are within normal limits. There are no obvious injuries requiring immediate attention.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important management step in preventing hepatitis B infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate testing for hepatitis B serology prior to treatment","Administer hepatitis B vaccination","Administer hepatitis B immunoglobulin","Administer hepatitis B vaccination and immunoglobulin","Advise the patient to wait until the window period is over before testing for hepatitis B"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires comprehensive post-exposure prophylaxis following sexual assault. The management priorities include prevention of sexually transmitted infections including hepatitis B, HIV, and bacterial infections, as well as addressing psychological support needs and arranging appropriate follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister hepatitis B vaccination and immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management step in this case. When a patient is non-immune (as this patient likely is, given her lack of childhood immunisations) and has been exposed to a potential source of hepatitis B through sexual assault where the assailant\u0027s status is unknown, both vaccination and immunoglobulin are recommended. The hepatitis B vaccine initiates active immunity which takes some time to take effect while the immunoglobulin provides immediate passive protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe above is recommended by the Australian Immunisation Handbook; however, we do note that guidelines vary and the Australian STI Guidelines recommend Hepatitis B immunoglobulin only where the assailant is known to be Hepatitis B virus antigen positive. Providing both hepatitis B vaccination and immunoglobulin offers the most comprehensive protection against potential hepatitis B infection when the exposure\u0027s hepatitis B status is unknown, as the administration of both significantly reduces the individuals risk if the assailant was to be unknowingly positive for Hepatitis B. For this reason we have chosen to select option D as the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering hepatitis B vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient in this high-risk scenario. While vaccination is important to develop long-term immunity, it takes time to develop protective antibody levels. In the context of sexual assault with unknown assailant status, the addition of immunoglobulin provides immediate protection during this vulnerable period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate testing for hepatitis B serology\u003C/strong\u003E would establish baseline status but should not delay the initiation of prophylaxis. While baseline testing is useful, it is not the most important step in management and is likely to be negative. Testing alone does not provide any protection against potential infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering hepatitis B immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient as it only provides temporary protection. Without concurrent vaccination, the patient would remain vulnerable to hepatitis B infection after the immunoglobulin\u0027s protective effect wanes, typically after 3-6 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvise the patient to wait until the window period is over\u003C/strong\u003E would miss the crucial opportunity to prevent hepatitis B infection. The window period is relevant for testing but not for initiating preventive measures. This approach would leave the patient completely unprotected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional aspects of care would include HIV post-exposure prophylaxis (which should be offered within 72 hours if there is significant risk), empiric treatment for other sexually transmitted infections, psychological support, and arrangement of follow-up care. Baseline testing for HIV and other STIs should be performed, with repeat testing at appropriate intervals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatitis B vaccination and immunoglobulin should be administered to non-immune individuals following sexual assault when the assailant\u0027s status is unknown.","Post-exposure prophylaxis for sexual assault should include consideration of HIV PEP, STI prophylaxis, and hepatitis B protection.","Comprehensive care after sexual assault includes medical, psychological, and forensic components with appropriate follow-up."],"references":["Freedman E. Clinical management of patients presenting following a sexual assault [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/july/clinical-management-of-patients-presenting-followi","Subramanian S, Green JS. The General Approach and Management of the Patient Who Discloses a Sexual Assault. Missouri Medicine [Internet]. 2015 May;112(3):211. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6170132/","Adult sexual assault - STI Guidelines Australia [Internet]. STI Guidelines Australia. 2021. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/populations-and-situations/adult-sexual-assault/","Australian immunisation handbook. Post-exposure prophylaxis for non-immune people exposed to a source that is positive for hepatitis B surface antigen or has an unknown status. Department of Health and Aged Care. Updated June 2023. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/resources/tables/table-post-exposure-prophylaxis-for-non-immune-people-exposed-to-a-source-that-is-positive-for-hepatitis-b-surface-antigen-or-has-an-unknown-status"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15913"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T07:55:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T07:55:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8604"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103394"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro